Problem 1. (16 points)

The data set at [http://mnstats.morris.umn.edu/Data/rnf6080.dat] records hourly rainfall at a certain location in Canada, every day from 1960 to 1980. The file is also given through the link labeled Data file Final Exam (rnf6080.dat).

  1. First, we need to load the data set into R using the command read.table(). Use the help function to learn what arguments this function takes. Once you have the necessary input, load the data set into R and make it a data frame called rain.df.
Solution

Type your answer here

rain.df = read.table("rnf6080.dat")
  1. How many rows and columns does rain.df have? (If there are not 5070 rows and 27 columns, something is wrong; check the previous part to see what might have gone wrong in the previous part.)
Solution

Type your answer here

nrow(rain.df)
## [1] 5070
ncol(rain.df)
## [1] 27

  1. Create a new column in the data frame called daily, which is the sum of the rightmost 24 columns. With this column, create a histogram of the values in this column, which are supposed to be daily rainfall values. What is wrong with this picture? Be thorough.
Solution

Type your answer here

rain.df$daily = rowSums(rain.df[,4:27])
hist(rain.df$daily, main = "Total Daily Rainfall", xlab = "Rainfall Amount", ylab = "Frequency")

#the x axis should be amounts of rainfall but the data goes negative. it looks like the data is skewed by some rainfall amounts that are -25000. 
min(rain.df$daily)
## [1] -23976
#the min of -23976 is throwing off the rest of the data
  1. Create a new data frame rain.df.fixed that takes the original and fixes it for any flaws you have discovered. Explain your fix and the reasoning behind it. Having done this, produce a new histogram with the corrected data and explain why this is more reasonable.
Solution

Type your answer here

rain.df.negatives = apply(rain.df, 1, function(x) any(x < 0))
rain.df.fixed = rain.df[!rain.df.negatives, ]
min(rain.df.fixed$daily)
## [1] 0
hist(rain.df.fixed$daily, main = "Total Daily Rainfall", xlab = "Rainfall Amount", ylab = "Frequency")

#the fix i did was to identify values in rain.df that were negative, and then create a new data frame (rain.df.fixed) that was just the original data frame without those negative values.
Problem 2. (4 points)

Syntax and class-typing.

  1. For each of the following commands, if the command executes without generating an error either explain why it should be an error, or explain the meaning behind the observed result. If the command does explicitly generate an error, explain why.
vector1 <- c("5", "12", "7", "32")
max(vector1)
sort(vector1)
sum(vector1)
Solution

Type your answer here

vector1 <- c(5, 12, 7, 32)
max(vector1)
## [1] 32
sort(vector1)
## [1]  5  7 12 32
sum(vector1)
## [1] 56
#the error was that the elements being put in the vector were strings and not numbers. the fix was to change the elements into numbers.
  1. Similar to part a, for the next series of commands (which are naturally divided into 3 sets), either explain their results, or why they should produce errors. Be sure to compare and contrast between them.
vector2 <- c("5",7,12)
vector2[2] + vector2[3]

dataframe3 <- data.frame(z1="5",z2=7,z3=12)
dataframe3[1,2] + dataframe3[1,3]

list4 <- list(z1="6", z2=42, z3="49", z4=126)
list4[[2]]+list4[[4]]
list4[2]+list4[4]
Solution

Type your answer here

#vector2 <- c("5",7,12)
#vector2[2] + vector2[3]
#this code does not work because the first element is a string. so R will read all elements as characters 

dataframe3 <- data.frame(z1="5",z2=7,z3=12)
dataframe3[1,2] + dataframe3[1,3]
## [1] 19
#this code does work because its creating a data frame and not a vector. R will keep elements as characters or numbers in a dataframe. 

list4 <- list(z1="6", z2=42, z3="49", z4=126)
list4[[2]]+list4[[4]]
## [1] 168
#list4[2]+list4[4]
#the first addition works because list[[2]] and list[[4]] with double brackets gets the elements themselves from the list where list[2] and list[4] with single brackets are getting the elements as sublist and R cannot add them together.

  1. The function rep() repeats a vector some number of times. Explain the difference between `rep(1:3, times=3) and rep(1:3, each=3).
Solution

Type your answer here

rep(1:3, times=3)
## [1] 1 2 3 1 2 3 1 2 3
#this repeats the sequence 1 2 3 three times in that order
rep(1:3, each=3)
## [1] 1 1 1 2 2 2 3 3 3
#this repeats each number in the sequence three times in order

#no, part c, and e are not compatible. part c sums up the total number of na's in each column while e is telling us how much rows had at least 1 na in them. these two numbers arent compatible because a row might have had multiple na's in different columns

The column COUNTYFP contains a numerical code for counties within each state. We are interested in Alameda County (county 1 in California), Santa Clara (county 85 in California), and Allegheny County (county 3 in Pennsylvania).

  1. Explain what the block of code below is supposed to accomplish, and how it does it.
acca <- c()
for (tract in 1:nrow(ca_pa)) {
  if (ca_pa$STATEFP[tract] == 6) {
    if (ca_pa$COUNTYFP[tract] == 1) {
      acca <- c(acca, tract)
    }
  }
}

accamhv <- c()
for (tract in acca) {
  accamhv <- c(accamhv, ca_pa[tract,10])
}
median(accamhv)
## [1] NA
Solution

Type your answer here

#the first bit of code is going through the STATEFP and COUNTYFP columns and checking if thier values are 6 and 1. if both of those are true that index is added to the acca vector. the second bit of code goes through acca and gets the value of the 10th column of that row and adds it to the accamhv vector. the last bit of code then gets the median of accahv vector

Problem 5. (4 points)

Write a function that takes as its argument two vectors, \(x\) and \(y\), produces a scatterplot, and calculates the correlation coefficient (using cor(x,y)) and test it on any two variables given in the calif_penn_2011.csv.

Solution

Type your answer here

correlate.coefficient = function(x, y) {
  plot(x, y, main = "Scatterplot", xlab = "X", ylab = "Y")
  cor(x, y) 
  }
correlate.coefficient(ca_pa$POPULATION, ca_pa$COUNTYFP)
